segments.text: We're at 2911 Georgia Street in North Carolina.
And I'm getting ready to chat with Mr. W.S.
Edmonds.
W.S.
Edmonds, E-D-M-O-N-D-A.
All right.
Say a sentence.
Is my mic working well?
This is now the second run.
We're checking to see that this works.

didn't get much out of it but then there was a ss market that i took a class under and i liked it and i did real well also one time i failed college algebra and then i took it in summer school and i made a flat 100. that was nice uh
I had to wear the uniform and I had, if you were caught, you were put on the bull ring.
I always thought that I only exceeded a certain amount I wouldn't have to work but maybe an hour.
I went up there that day and Colonel Anderson said we don't keep books that way so I had to walk through the ring for four hours.
Describe Colonel Andy.
Well he was kind of a short fellow very athletic.
I didn't

care for that very much as a student, but I had to, oh, I do remember, I think it was Colonel Andy, that constantly, it seemed like every week, somebody would put a flag up on the flagpole, and he'd have to pay somebody to go up there and get that flag down.
And that was quite an occasion.
We'd all be around there, and I'm kind of kidding you, you know, I don't think he liked that.
Now, he lived, Anderson's lived on campus?
Yes, I'm sure he did.
I don't even know what house.
I knew quite a few of the homes that lived on there.
Before I went to A&M, I used to deliver newspapers to all of them around here.
Oh, which paper?
The Eagle.
I wrote the Inner Urban, the college where I lived there, at the North Cape.
In Dubai, I picked up the paper.
I was the only carrier in the Eagle.
And as the police would go out, I would throw newspapers out along the trolley line.
And they'd get the samples.
I had about maybe 100 prescribers.
They didn't count the papers on me or anything like that.
And one of my favorite things is to go by the mess hall and take the papers in there, and they'd give you a good hand check.
Do you remember what, what your pay was for that delivery?
How much money did you make as a paper boy?
And do you remember what the subscription was?
How much did they pay for the paper?
Did you have to collect the money?
No, you just delivered.
And you were the only Eagles delivery boy for the whole campus.
I was kind of handed down from my family.
My mother was a boy.
And at one time, Linwood Boyette, who later became the elder of Texas University.
And incidentally, they're the ones that gave the first steer to Texas University.
Who was that now?
Boyette?
Linwood Boyette was the son of an uncle of mine, Doug A. Boyette.
And as I understand, they gave the first steer to Texas University, the first vehicle.
Now, he was a yell leader at Texas University.
And then later, his brother became yell leader, Jack Boyette, at Texas University.
He became yell leader, and Jack had held the legal route, and he turned it over to me.
Now, Boyette's owned the property east of the campus theater, didn't they, at Northgate?
They owned up through...
Well, pharmacy, where Lupo's is now, Lipton Pharmacy on the other side of Spar.
I remember Spar told my grandfather, he said, that's the best thing you ever did was get me to buy 10 feet, I believe, from back to set my building back.
On downtown.
When you were in high school, what businesses were there at Northgate?
Uh...
I don't remember too much about part of anything being there.
As I understand, old Charlie's Grocery was there.
That was later on.
Might have been when I was in high school.
And that building up there was a wooden building.
At one time, I think my grandfather, somebody had a grocery store there.
They had the gates when I was going there.
They didn't lock the gates, but they had the gates around them and the door there with the fence.
I remember one time my folks built a skating rink.
Somehow or another, the university didn't care for them to go over there at night to the skating rink, so they just put the skating rink off-limits.
And the kids couldn't come off the campus to go to the skating rink.
A lot of them went to Brian's on the weekend for the picture show.
They had a picture show in Brian's.
There wasn't one in College Station.
Not that I know of.
What was there at Southgate?
Were there any businesses over there yet?
when you were in high school uh that's what i remember all they were was just over there in california and the campus faced the railroad well there was two railroads up there of course
And they had the, incidentally, that's where they had these carts that they pulled stuff on.
They were kind of four-wheel wagons, rather narrowly, with baggage carts.
And that's what the Aggies used to haul stuff to the bond farm.
As a matter of fact, they took our outhouse.
We had an outhouse there.
And...
Well, I didn't object to that because you go up to the college and they didn't have any bulges.
I think they took several outhouses around and that's it.
Let's see, back to the campus.
Do you remember how you registered?
How did a student sign up for courses?
Well, there wasn't really a problem at all.
No, but did you stand, did you go to some thesis and stand in line?
Oh, there was no line.
The main thing was to get the money to register.
Do you remember what it cost when you first entered A&M?
Well, I remember my stepfather was working for the power plant at Collin.
And he came home with his check, I suppose it was either a weekly check or a two-week check, and said, you take this money and go away.
He said, I want you to go to Collin.
Now, that couldn't have been very much for him.
And you said you had to buy your own uniforms you did because you weren't physically Describe the uniform show or what?
We had
Well, of course, the seniors, I believe, had a little bit better hat with a stiff brim around it.
And, of course, if you were in the artillery, you wore red and blue infantry and signal corps.
All of that was on the hat that the seniors had with the gold braid coming out.
How did you get introduced
all of the Aggie traditions of whipping out and all that.
How did a fish in those days get prepared?
I was with the company.
You were assigned, even though I had a hernia, I was just an ROTC and had good ROTC classes.
And what outfit were you in?
Which one?
Did it have a nickname?
But you had to go over and make formation in the afternoon?
Where did y'all drill?
You were just in front of the dormitory.
I had to go there and be available when they called the kids to be with the first one to the room to run an errand for the upper class.
And the one thing I liked about it when you would go to, I believe you got, when you used the board, let's say,

sophomores were usually kind of bad they were the roughest but if they got too rough then the juniors would come along and that that would slow it down so there was a control there uh really and there were one or two arguments that couldn't take it at all
Do you remember what kind of paddle did they use?
What size was it?
What was it made out of?
kind of did a little artwork on their paddles, and they had specific paddles.
We always enjoyed the day when they got where it was called, but it was the day that the underclassmen would paddle the upper class.
Was that fish day?
Fish day, yeah.
Did you paddle somebody?
So even though you didn't eat on campus, you were expected to do chores, run errands for upperclassmen.
And how long at night would you have to do that?
I think it was up to about 7 o'clock.
After that, some nights, it was just during the afternoon, the time they went to jail, really.
But I did miss out on sometimes, what you call it, an air outing, where they put you in the paddock and they make the guys leave you gone, you know.
Did you...
So you would get up and go to your 8 o'clock class.
You didn't have to go over and stand inspection before breakfast.
Oh, you did?
Okay.
And then you'd go to class.
Describe a full day of classes.
What did you do all day?
Well, it seemed like the classes just ran from more or less 8 o'clock until noon, and then 1 o'clock to 5.
I think the longest class was probably, I took it to agriculture, that was generally, that was actually pretty well free from 5 o'clock.
What was your major, do you remember?
Well, I thought...
I started mechanical engineering and I dropped mechanical engineering and ended up with agriculture administration and also I took cotton marketing classes which I really enjoyed.
I ended up later when I left A&M going into cotton in New Orleans.
I really enjoyed that.
Now when you were in class, did you attend regularly?
Did you go to class regularly, regularly, and they checked the role?
Did you all ever do any mischief in class?
Oh, no.
Not at that time.
Not at all.
What about going to sleep in class?
No, you didn't do that either.
I did that when I was in OCS at Fort Chill.
I stood in the corner for four hours.
During the day,
If you wanted to get a Coca Cola, or to just take a break, where did y'all go during the day cases?
I had the money I got a banana split.
I think it might have been about was that in the YMCA?
That is downstairs in the YMCA.
They also had
Do you remember getting your fish haircut?
No not really.
I do, it comes about, I do remember there was one comrade down there that joined the Brines, and it was a man in Brines that had received a hot check.
And so, he got all the, about 10 or 12 of us, I didn't know it until later, and interviewed us, and that man couldn't pick out who had did it.
I was completely innocent because
I had gone in the store and I had gone in there.
But I was one of about 10 or 12.
And he kept man didn't know who really did it.
He thinks like that.
And I do remember the common dance
As a student, what were the things that you all knew were totally prohibited?
You might do pranks or play jokes, but there must have been some limit.
What were the things that were off limits?
The main thing was getting out of the uniform, as I remember, and getting put on the bull ring.
Now, where was the bull ring then?
When you walked the bull ring, where was that?
Well, it was either in the drill field or you'd walk to what's called a fish tank.
I believe it was a fish tank.
I remember one thing that a friend of mine that I knew fairly well
He was living in the dormitory and he had gotten some whiskey and he was selling it for the dancers.
He'd pour up little bottles and made a little money one week and did it again.
About the second time though he did it, the
I've forgotten the communist name, but he called him in.
Colonel Andy?
Huh?
Was it Colonel Andy?
No, it wasn't Colonel Andy.
Somebody, oh, okay.
He called him in and said, now, I know what you're doing.
We haven't had any trouble, but I don't want you to do that anymore.
Well, that was the end of that.
He didn't kick him out of school or anything like that, but he called him in and said, now,

don't do that anymore in terms of alcohol where where could a student have bought beer when you were an undergraduate there's very few places if I know all there were a few pieces that have people that bootlegged whiskey
you could get bootleg whiskey fairly easy over around Brenham in Washington County.
But you had to leave Brazos County to get it.
Pretty well.
There were some people that handled, that bootlegged here in Brazos County.
But there wasn't that much drinking, you would say, back in those days.
There really wasn't.
Now, when I got here, people drove to Whiskey Bridge.
towards Snook and bought whiskey just across the river.
Did that exist then, that place?

No, the only thing they had was some bootleg whiskey and that was, or there might have been maybe a couple of places out in Brazos County where if you knew somebody you could go in there and get a little bit.
And in Washington County,
What, what about beer?
Where could you buy beer?
No, because you had to roll your own for one day.
And I don't remember anybody ever spoke.
Both of them didn't have enough money.
